  "prompt": "Graph Theory: What does it mean if vertices are adjacent?",
  "response": "In graph theory, two vertices (or nodes) are said to be **adjacent** if there is an edge (or connection) directly linking them. In other words, if you have a graph \\( G \\) consisting of a set of vertices \\( V \\) and a set of edges \\( E \\), two vertices \\( u \\) and \\( v \\) in \\( V \\) are adjacent if the edge \\( (u, v) \\) is included in \\( E \\).\n\nFor example, in a simple undirected graph, if you have vertices labeled \\( A \\) and \\( B \\), and there is an edge connecting \\( A \\) and \\( B \\), then \\( A \\) and \\( B \\) are adjacent. The concept of adjacency is fundamental in graph theory and is used in various applications, such as traversing graphs, analyzing connectivity, and in algorithms like breadth-first search (BFS) and depth-first search (DFS).",
